Fillmore:
1. Quoted passage:
“The potential projects or management actions being considered by the FPBGSA include, but are not necessarily limited to, the following:  
• Supporting Cienega Springs Restoration project as drought refuge;  
• Monitoring wells at Cienega Springs Restoration project site;  
• Installation of shallow monitoring wells across basin;  
• Buying supplemental water when available;  
• Additional water quality sampling;  
• Arundo removal; and  
• Subsidence studies – critical infrastructure, City of Fillmore & Town of Piru gravity systems… ”  
(Groundwater Sustainability Plan Fillmore Basin, Section 4, p. 4-1)

Another passage describing the first project:  
“The FPBGSA desires to dampen the impacts of groundwater extraction by supporting the restoration efforts at the Cienega Restoration Project. The primary action being considered by the FPBGSA is to provide supplemental groundwater to the restoration program during multi-year droughts when the shallow groundwater levels decline below the Critical Water Level.”  
(GSP, Section 4.1, p. 4-2)

2. Reasoning:
The listed projects focus on supplying supplemental groundwater to a riparian restoration project, installing monitoring wells, vegetation removal, and similar actions. None of the projects describe an intentional recharge (e.g., spreading basins, injection wells, or in-lieu recharge) whose stated purpose is to enhance aquifer storage. Therefore, the GSP does not present a “recharge project” with explicit environmental benefits.

ANSWER: No, Modest Confidence, 60%

1. Relevant text quotations

a. “Beneficial users and uses in the Basin include:  
• Agricultural and domestic well owners;  
• The City of Fillmore (municipal well operator);  
• UWCD and a number of mutual water companies (public water systems);  
• Santa Clara River GDEs, primarily the East Grove and Cienega Riparian Complex areas…;  
• …Disadvantaged communities, located in the southwest and east portions of the Basin…” (p. 2-14)

b. “4.1 Project #1: Supporting the Cienega Springs Restoration Project as a Drought Refuge…  
The mitigative effects of this action include:  
• Providing a refuge for vegetation and wildlife during a period of prolonged drought;  
• Supplying water that can be used to irrigate additional land parcels…;  
• Providing a natural seed supply…;  
• Possible use as a seed source area for a ‘seed bank’ …” (pp. 4-2)

c. “4.5 Project #5: Additional Water Quality Sampling  
The FPBGSA will consider augmenting the water quality network in the vicinity of Pole Creek Fan. This area was identified… as having limited water quality information on analytes that are near a regulatory threshold.” (p. 4-5)

2. Reasoning

The GSP explicitly lists key beneficial users (GDEs, domestic/drinking-water users, DACs) and provides at least one management action (Project #1) that directly benefits GDEs, plus another action aimed at protecting water quality for drinking-water users. However, while DACs are identified, no specific project is described that clearly benefits DACs, and tribes are noted as absent. Thus, beneficial users are identified and some impacts/benefits are described, but not comprehensively for all key groups.

ANSWER: Somewhat, Fairly Confident, 75%
